{ Hello and Welcome to Lifetime Repertoires: The Pirc Defence!  This course provides a complete repertoire for Black, based on the Pirc Defence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  We include White's possible deviations on move 2 and 3, making it a comprehensive Repertoire against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4   Let's talk about the nature and history of the Pirc Defence for a moment.  The Pirc Defence is not a 'Classical' Opening. What is the definition of 'Classical' in Chess? The Classical values go back to the beginning of Chess as a subject of systematic research. Concepts like 'controlling the centre with pawns', 'developing pieces quickly', 'play for quick castling', 'keep a sound pawn structure' were developed by the greats of the past; names like Steinitz or Tarrasch come to mind.  While most of the mentioned values are present in the Pirc, one crucial point is neglected: controlling the centre with pawns. Black is happily allowing White to occupy the centre with the perfect pawn duo e4 & d4, which quickly can be supplemented with an additional pawn on f4 if White wishes to do so. Giving the opponent that much leeway in the centre was frowned upon and even believed to be a foolish endeavour for a long time.  In the 1920s, when openings like the Nimzo-Indian and the Gr√ºnfeld already had acquired some credibility, answering @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  with  1...d6  or  1...g6  was considered a mistake. In his classic book about the New York Tournament 1924, Alekhine called ... g6 a joke opening and attached a question mark to the move. At the time, these ...d6/...g6 Defences to e4 were usually called Old Indian.  About two decades later, after the Second World War, this setup was adopted by two players. The first one was GM Vasja Pirc, a multiple champion of Yugoslavia, the second one was Anatoli Ufimzew, a strong Soviet master. Ufimzew never was allowed to play outside of the Soviet Union - he surely would have earned the GM title otherwise. These two players, completely independent from one another, analyzed and played the opening frequently. Nowadays, the name 'Pirc Defence' is commonly accepted for the subject of our course, the sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  . In the past, the name 'Pirc-Ufimtsev Defence' or even just 'Ufimzev Defence' was also frequently used. We decided to use 'Pirc Defence', as this name is by far the commonly accepted one.  Pirc and Ufimtsev introduced and refined the opening, which quickly gained momentum in the 1950s and 1960s. Legendary players and World Champions like Smyslov, Botvinnik, and Bobby Fischer played the Pirc, in Fischer's case even in the World Championship Match against Spassky. In modern times, the Pirc has attracted ambitious players like Svidler, Mamedyarov, and Morozevich. Many strong players use it as an occasional weapon to fight for a win, including World Champion Magnus Carlsen.  So, what are some key concepts of the Pirc?  - Black does not immediately place a pawn in the centre but prefers to attack White's pawn centre later. Black has many ways to do that, for example, with ...e7-e5 or ...c7-c5. Black might even wait with such a strike even longer and first expand on the queenside with ...b5. Black has many options and possible pawn structures to choose from.  - Black's play may provoke White to be overly aggressive, which can lead to overextension. White's space advantage can backfire, in particular, if White has advanced pawns around their King  - The struggle between White's centre and Black trying to fight it can often lead to very concrete, tactical play. Black needs to play actively. Otherwise, White's space might be a decisive factor. We have selected lines that go for sharp counterplay and pose problems for our opponent. Passive play is a recipe for disaster in the Pirc.  - The Pirc is less explored compared to more frequently played main lines. It is possible to find new ideas early on, which is more difficult in mainstream openings.  - On the non-professional level, White often has no preparation against the Pirc. White players usually focus on the most popular moves 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...c6 and 1...e6 but neglect other openings. Against the Pirc, White has no widely known 'spoilsport' option. There is no 'Exchange Variation' or a System like the Alapin in the Sicilian, making the Pirc an excellent practical weapon to play for a win. The drawing percentage in the Pirc is low.  - Move orders can be tricky to master for both sides. We have selected lines that share common ideas, like an early ...a6 and ...Nc6. This reduces the danger of accidentally entering a line that you have not prepared.  Before we talk about the contents of the repertoire, we'd like to discuss the concept of a Lifetime Repertoire for a moment. When Christof wrote the introduction for Lifetime Repertoires: 1.c4/1.Nf3 he compiled a list of five criteria that served as a guideline. We want to base our criteria on these points but need to modify them slightly, given that we are talking about a repertoire for the black pieces in a sharp and ambitious opening.  Here are the criteria for the Pirc Defence.  1. It must be fundamentally sound.  2. Should be based on well-tested lines and profound new ideas.  3. Allows some flexibility and modifiability for the future.  4. Usable for a wide range of playing levels.  5. Sets complex practical problems to unbalance the game and fight for a win with Black. This means there is risk involved, and 'unclear' positions must be embraced and not avoided.  The last point in this list already indicates that we don't play the Pirc to simplify the game and draw. Often we choose ambitious moves that pour more oil into the fire, aiming to unbalance the game. Whenever possible, we selected lines that lead to complications and exciting positions.  This also means that not every line will end in a 0.00 evaluation or an advantage for Black. It is acceptable if White has a slight edge in computer evaluations, as long as it is difficult for White to play and Black has chances.  Now, let's have a look at the essential variations to get you started with the Pirc! }
