ble to fight these lines with the same approach each time. You need to look at each one and learn and play the best reply, as the small differences matter a lot.  The Austrian Attack is probably the part of the Pirc that demands the most memorization; there is no way to avoid that. White's play is rather concrete and aggressive, and our responses need to be precise. In slower lines, like the Classical Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Black can get away with knowing only some concrete lines and ideas. If you try to fight the Austrian Attack with vague ideas, you might just get destroyed. The upside is: if you know what to do, you'll be fine.  In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on the most important lines that you'll encounter in your games or that demand a precise response that you should know. }
4... Bg7
{ Now White's main move is  5.Nf3  by far. It makes a lot of sense to develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else.  White may deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like  5.Bd3  or  5.a3  , but these options are not so relevant in the context of this Quickstarter Guide. They have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main lines after  5.Nf3  .  We'll have a look at  5.e5  , though. This move requires a precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble. }
5. e5
{ Early e4-e5 advances are common in the Pirc. Objectively speaking, we don't need to be afraid of White's rather premature attack.   White has only developed a single piece so far and his King is still in the centre. White's attack might easily backfire, but it requires precise play by Black. }
5... Nfd7
{ We like this move the most. Note that after  5...dxe5  6.dxe5!?  is an interesting move for White. After the Queen trade White gets the easier game and chances for slight advantage.   The Knight retreat to d7 is far more aggressive, planning to tear down White's centre with ...c5 quickly. White's most common move after  5...Nfd7!  is  6.Nf3  but we'll also briefly check the rare move  6.Bc4  which leads to interesting complications.  White also has  6.e6  but after  6...fxe6  7.Nf3  c5  we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppnppbp/3p2p1/4P3/3P1P2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  c5  7.e6  fxe6 }
6. Nf3
{ This looks natural and is played almost exclusively in this position. } 6...
c5
{ We crack White's centre immediately. Every tempo counts, therefore we don't wait with this principled move. After  6...O-O  we would transpose to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.e5  Nfd7  which is not part of our repertoire. We prefer  6...dxe5!  in this line, as we will examinehere in the dedicated chapter.   Now White has some options. The most popular move is  7.exd6  , but you'll certainly meet some others, in particular in faster time control games. }
7. exd6 { This has been played most of the time here by White. } 7... O-O
{ We think it's the best continuation to bring our King to a safer position. This is confirmed by the results, with Black scoring above 50% in Megabase 2021. }
8. Be3
{ The usual response by White. He supports the d4-pawn and prepares to castle long. Instead,  8.dxe7+?  is too greedy. Black has excellent play for the pawn, for example after  8...Qxe7+  9.Qe2  Qxe2+  10.Nxe2  Re8  . The lead in development is one thing, but the weaknesses caused by f4 amplify White's problems. }
8... exd6
{ We have regained the pawn and our Bishop enjoys an excellent diagonal. } 9.
Qd2 { White hurries to bring his King to a safer place. } 9... Nc6
{ We increase the pressure on d4. } 10. O-O-O Qa5
{ The last few moves were logical. Now White has a wide choice of how to develop further. We think Black is fine in any case, usually organizing with ...Nf6 and ...Bf5 next. }
11. a3
{ White avoids a possible ...Nb4 move and gets rid of the potential threat of us to take the a2-pawn with our Queen once the c3-Knight moves.  White has also tried the move  11.Kb1  which is answered in the same way as  11.a3  . Our setup with ...Nf6 and ...Bf5 works well in both cases. }
11... Nf6
{ We free the way of our light-squared Bishop. At the same time, our f6-Knight takes an eye on the light central squares e4 and d5.   We also threaten to jump to g4 in some cases. }
12. h3 { White takes control over g4. } 12... Bf5
{ Completing the development and the setup mentioned earlier. We like Black's position and like to point out an interesting idea worth knowing after White's next move. }
13. Bd3 b5
{ That's the point! This pawn-push initiates fun complications. After  14.Nxb5  Nb4!  15.Nxd6  Bxd3  16.cxd3  Nfd5!  Black has excellent play and a dangerous initiative. }
