1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4
{ This chapter and the following examine the Austrian Attack, which starts with  4.f4  . White builds a broad pawn centre and often tries to attack the Kingside later.  The f-pawn supports the pawn advance e4-e5, which is the most critical idea available for White. A supported pawn on e5 will seriously hamper our strong g7-Bishop, which is why fighting this idea is a crucial element of Black's strategy.  The Austrian Attack has always been regarded as the mainline of the Pirc and remains very popular on all levels. A very understandable statistic, as White's play is aggressive and very straightforward. The direct nature of White's strategy, however, is also helping Black to some extent. With  4.f4  White immediately commits to a central structure, so we know what to deal with straight away.  The game's direction is not as apparent after a more flexible move like  4.Be3  , when White might still play f4 later, but may also play with f2-f3 or Nf3, depending on Black's setup. The consequence is that the lines after  4.f4  are less ridden with transpositions and more forcing.   Let's talk a bit about the various lines.  A. The most popular line is  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Bd3  , which we answer with  6...Nc6  , aiming for ...e5. This line is examined in three chapters.   B. Instead of  6.Bd3  as in A, White may also play  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Be3  , which hints at a possible queenside castling. This line is examinedhere in a dedicated chapter.   C. After  4.f4  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  White also has the aggressive option  6.e5  , which is examinedhere in a dedicated chapter, as well.  D. Finally, there are early deviations on move 5 or 6, which are examined in the current chapter.  Before we check the possible sidelines @@StartBracket@@D@@EndBracket@@ in this chapter, we'd like to address an important point.  At various moments White has the option to play e4-e5, aggressively advancing in the centre. It is not possible to fight these lines with the same approach each time. You need to look at each one and learn how to play the best reply, as the small differences matter a lot.  The Austrian Attack is probably the part of the Pirc that demands the most memorization; there is no way to avoid that. White's play is rather concrete and aggressive, and our responses need to be precise. In slower lines, like the Classical Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  , Black can get away with knowing only some concrete lines and ideas.  If you try to fight the Austrian Attack with vague ideas, you might just get destroyed. The upside is: if you know what to do, you'll be fine.  Let's start and have a look at White's sidelines on move 5 and  6. }
4... Bg7
{ Now White's main move is  5.Nf3  by far. It makes a lot of sense to develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else.  In the current chapter, we examine ways for White to deviate from the main lines. The following lines are relatively rare.  We don't get too detailed here and instead focus on the critical lines in the next chapters. The more dangerous exceptions from the main lines are variations that feature a quick e4-e5, attacking us quickly. }
5. Bd3
