6. Be2
{ This is a rather rare move, but we need to be prepared.  Most importantly, our common plan to develop with  6...Nc6  does not work now, as  7.O-O  e5  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  10.fxe5  Ng4  11.Nb5  is great for White. This can be compared with the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  O-O  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Be2  when  7. ..e5?  does not work, either.  Here White has made an even more useful move than a3, which puts the whole idea out of business. However, we have a different idea. The Pirc is very versatile and you need to be ready to play the right pawn break, according to circumstances. }
6... c5
{ Seeing that breaking with ...e5 is difficult, we go for a different approach.  Due to the Bishop position on e2, White's e4-pawn is just protected by the c3-Knight. We will take advantage of that and attack White's centre from the flank.  Note that after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  c5?!  is not that good because White's d3-Bishop protects e4 as well. Therefore  6.Bd3  c5?!  7.dxc5  is good for White, as  7...Qa5?  fails to  8.cxd6  .   With the Bishop on e2, after  6.Be2  c5!  7.dxc5  Qa5  White has no time to take on d6, as we threaten the pawn on e4. Still, taking on c5 is White's most popular move by far. }
7. dxc5
{ This is the main move by far and has been played almost exclusively from this position by White. }
7... Qa5
{ The Queen move is the idea behind 6... c5. The Queen pins the c3-Knight and we threaten to take the e4-pawn with our f6-Knight. }
