1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be3
{ In this chapter, we deal with an important deviation from the mainline  6.Bd3  .  White plays  6.Be3  , which develops the dark-squared Bishop first. The move has got several advantages:  1 White strengthens his control over the d4-square;  2 White is just two moves away from castling queenside;  3 White makes it more difficult for Black to push ...c5.  But there must be some disadvantage, as otherwise, the whole world would prefer to play Be3, right? On the downside, there is:  1 White's e4-square is not supported by Bd3. In some variations, we might try to exploit this weakness.  2 White is not able to castle kingside on the next move. Black's King is already in safety, whereas White's King does not feel comfortable in the centre of the board.  3 The e3-Bishop is quite vulnerable at the moment. It's unprotected, and we can attack it by playing ...Ng4 under the right circumstances.   Let's think about our strategic options. Aiming for the ...e5-break is quite difficult. The immediate  6...e5  leads to an advantage for White after  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.fxe5  Ng4  10.Bg5  .   Preparing the e5-push with  6...Nc6  is also not that attractive. Our c6-Knight attacks e5 and d4 but both squares are firmly under White's control and he might try to punish us immediately by playing  7.e5  .  In the resulting position, we lack the...c5-break because our c6-Knight is blocking the c-pawn. OK, let's forget about playing e7-e5 for the time being. We have another option! }
6... b6
{ We go for the ...c5-pawn push, instead of the ...e5-break. The immediate  6...c5  fails, so we need to invest a tempo in preparing the move.   Furthermore, we can put more pressure on e4, a pawn that is quite vulnerable at the moment, by playing ...Bb7 next. After  6...b6  , we will frequently meet a particular pawn formation.  Often White will play e4-e5 while we push c7-c5. This formation is called 'Diamond formation' due to all pawns between the a-file and e-file being on dark squares. It indeed looks like a crystal or even a diamond. Creative names like that are fun and even help to visualize and memorize ideas. }
7. e5
{ White plays aggressively and pushes his e-pawn. The move is recommended by Chris Baker in A Startling Chess Opening Repertoire. }
7... Ng4 { We attack the unprotected Bishop on e3 and gain some time. } 8. Bg1
{ White wants to keep his dark-squared Bishop.   On the one hand, the Bishop is needed to control the dark squares and support the centre. On the other hand, White intends to play h3 soon, pushing the black Knight to a less ideas square on h6. }
8... c5
{ We reach the diamond structure, which we outlined earlier. White's centre is under severe pressure now. }
9. h3 Nh6
{ White has played aggressively, but the advanced pawn centre is already under heavy fire.  White's most popular move is  10.d5  now, but we'll check some alternatives to illustrate the dangers of White being over-extended.  One general problem is the Bishop on g1. It is difficult for White to move it back to e3, as we would jump with our Knight to f5 and kick the Bishop again. }
10. Bd3
{ A natural move, but we get to destroy White's centre now. It turns out that Be4 is no problem for us. }
10... cxd4 11. Be4
{ A huge mistake. We can't save the Rook on a8 now but get enough material and an overwhelming position in return. }
11... dxc3 12. Bxa8 cxb2 13. Rb1 Qc7
{ Black has a decisive advantage after this move, but  13...Nd7  or  13...Ba6  are equally strong. We are not even material down for this overwhelming position.  White's King is stuck in the centre and this part of the board is quickly opening now. }
