{ Black has two good moves at this point. The alternative to our suggestion is  7...Bg4  because we might get rid of the f3-Knight, one of White's defenders of the dark central squares. The drawback of  7...Bg4  is the reply  8.e5!  when White reaches a slightly improved version of 7.e5.   This is no problem, as the immediate action  7...e5  in the centre is possible and good. We quickly provoke a crisis in the centre and force White to decide between various possible pawn formations. White's main answers are the captures  8.fxe5  and  8.dxe5  .  We will also check the move  8.d5  which recently gained some momentum. }
8. dxe5
{ This is a lot less popular than  8.fxe5  but White has an interesting idea in mind. }
8... dxe5 9. f5
{ The principled way to play after 8. dxe5. White's idea is to gain space on the Kingside and later start an attack with ideas like Qe1-h4, combined with Bg5 or Bh6+Ng5.   White could also start with  9.Qe1  but we are fine after  9...exf4  10.Bxf4  Be6  . White has good piece play, but our pawn structure is preferable long-term. }
9... Nb4
{ We think this is the best move,  9...Nb4  has two points. The first one is to grab the Bishop-pair, but the second one is less obvious.  One of White's attack ideas might be the pin after Bg5, which could turn out to be annoying if combined with Nd5. By moving the c6-knight, we free the c-pawn to prepare c6, limiting the scope of White's c3-Knight. }
