lly replies  7.a4  when after  7...Nc6  8.d5  we have the opportunity to play  8...Nb4!   So what about ...b5? Do we ever play it? Yes, there are some cases, but we prioritize ...Nc6 and play ...e5 next, if possible. If White stops this idea, ...b5 becomes more relevant.  In the present chapter, we will look at lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bf4  Nc6  8.h3  when we play  8...b5  . This advance needs to be well-timed; Earlier ...b5 pushes don't work well due to e4-e5 ideas. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  b5?!  8.e5  are excellent for White, and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  b5?!  or  7.Bf4  b5?!  are similar stories.   The right mindset about @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  is: we improve the ...Nc6/...e5 idea, and ...b5 is a good later option to resort to if White prevents ...e5.  So, what does White do in the Classical, what's the strategy? Well, White wants to keep central control and retrain Black's ideas to break out of the spatial disadvantage. White often plays 'small moves', like h3, Re1, and a4, to improve his position step by step.  White does not have a clear-cut way forward in the Classical, it's all about flexibility and depends on Black's setup. There are direct ideas that can lead to a sharpening of the play, though. The one that we need to watch out for is e4-e5, the pawn advance. White often plays moves that support this plan, like Re1, Bf4, and h3 @@StartBracket@@ h3 takes away a possible ...Ng4 in reply to e4-e5 @@EndBracket@@.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  White has many 'small moves', as mentioned, and can play them in various orders. This makes it difficult to organize the coverage. However, we ca