{ The most common move in this position. White gains space in the centre and wins a tempo on the Knight. }
8... Na7
{ Our move a6 has cleared this unusual square for our Knight. At first glance, it looks misplaced. But looks can be deceiving; there are some interesting points of the quirky Knight move. This line has been played twice by Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Ian Nepomniachtchi and David Navara, with good results.  Let's talk about White's next move because it will influence the course of the game significantly. We think that White's best move is  9.a4  when it's our turn to make an important decision. Let's have a look at why other moves than  9.a4  are less critical. We'll check  9.h3  and  9.Bg5  to illustrate matters. }
