4... Bg7 5. Be2
{ As mentioned in the overview on move four, White has a wide choice here. The move  5.Be2  , called the 'Classical Variation', is examined in the current and the subsequent chapter. There are many 'Classical Variations' in various openings, and the Pirc has one, too.  What is the definition of 'Classical' in Chess? The Classical values go back to the beginning of Chess as a subject of systematic research. Concepts like 'controlling the centre with pawns', 'developing pieces quickly', 'play for quick castling', 'keep a sound pawn structure' were developed by the greats of the past; names like Steinitz or Tarrasch come to mind.  A 'Classical Variation' follows these guidelines - sensible and logical, without being too fancy. In the Classical Pirc, White plays  5.Be2  and 6.O-O, when Black has various options. We'll talk more about the general strategy on move six. }
