{ We go for our standard move ...Nc6, adding pressure on the dark centre squares and preparing ...e5 next. White now needs to decide if our plan ...e5 should be allowed or stopped, at least for the moment.   After  8.a4  e5  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p1np1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  e5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p1np1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3  e5  we transpose to lines examined in the second chapter on the Classical Pirchere.  In this chapter, we discuss all scenarios with ...e5. White's other approach is to stop ...e5 or make it more difficult to play.  The most important moves to try are @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p1np1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d5  and  8.Bf4  . The move  8.Bf4  we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bf4  Nc6  8.h3  . We'll also have a look at @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p1np1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg5  , but this version of Bg5 is less pointed than @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  Nc6  8.Bg5  as we will see. }
8. d5
{ The most common move in this position. White gains space in the centre and wins a tempo on the Knight. }
8... Na7
{ Our move a6 has cleared this unusual square for our Knight. At first glance, it looks misplaced. But looks can be deceiving; there are some interesting points of the quirky Knight move. This line has been played twice by Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Ian Nepomniachtchi and David Navara, with good results.  Let's talk about White's next move because it will influence the course of the game significantly. We think that White's best move is  9.a4  when it's our turn to make an important decision. Let's have a look at why other moves than  9.a4  are less critical. We'll check  9.h3  and  9.Bg5  to illustrate matters. }
9. a4
{ Move  9.a4  is the most challenging test of Black's line. Now ...b5 and ...Nb5 ideas are off the table for the moment.  Now we need to decide how to set up the central pawn formation. This flexibility and scope for creativity incomparably early stages of the game is an appealing virtue of the Pirc. }
9... e5
{ We suggest going for the closed central formation. In the second chapter on the Classical about the ...e5 lines, we discuss these structures, but in lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  Nc6  8.h3  e5  9.d5  Ne7  our Knight is on e7.   At first glance, having the Knight on a7 instead looks ridiculous, but the situation is not as clear-cut as you might think. We'll discuss the merits of the Knight in a moment, but before we'd like to point out that Black has a reasonable alternative with  9...e6  , which has been tested in games by Levon Aronian and David Navara.  Keeping the long diagonal open with  9...e6  is the more solid choice, but we think that  9...e5  leads to fascinating fights and is a good practical weapon. The resulting positions are quite similar to a Classical King's Indian, and White might be unfamiliar with these pawn structures.  A key idea for White is a pawn advance on the Queenside, often involving c4-c5, aiming to open the c-file. This is not so easy to achieve, as the c3-Knight is blocking the pawn. Black's plan is a lot easier to implement: move the f6-Knight and play ...f5 to start advancing on the Kingside.   Let's discuss some concrete moves now. The position is unexplored; we only found one game in which White played the less critical  10.dxe6  when  10...Bxe6  and ...Nc6 next gives Black an easy game. Our pieces are actively placed and we can play against the e4-pawn.   White should try to make headway in the closed structure and avoid the en-passant capture. We'll examine  10.b4  as the starting move of the analysis, as White can hardly do without this move on the Queenside. }
10. b4
{ We'll look at  10.b4  Bd7  11.a5  and White's @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/npp1ppbp/p2p1np1/3P4/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  e5  10.a5  Bd7  11.b4  is a sensible move order, too. An interesting question arises after a move like  10.Bf1  .   Should Black play  10...a5  and stop White's a-pawn? This would be a good idea if our Knight wouldn't be on a7. On a7, it does not connect at all to a dark-squared blockade. Playing ...a5 would make much more sense if the Knight would be on d7 or even b8.   After moves other than  10.b4  or  10.a5  we won't play ...a5, but rather continue in the same way as we do after the pawn moves. Play ...Bd7 first, then proceed on the Kingside with ...h6, ...Nh7 and ...f5. White will likely play one of the pawn moves anyway, getting into positions very similar to  10.b4  or  10.a5 }
10... Bd7 11. Bf1
{ We'll take that as the mainline. White can also play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/npp1ppbp/p2p1np1/3P4/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  e5  10.a5  immediately when  11...Bd7  12.Bf1  is a logical continuation.  The move Bf1 is very useful for White, as it lends additional cover to the e4-pawn. This makes c3 mobile, which will be necessary for any Queenside action. }
11... h6
{ We suggest to prepare ...f5 with ...h6 and ...Nh7. Going ...Ne8 and ...f5 always runs into Ng5-e6 ideas, which we should prevent.   Now we'll have a look at two possible plans for White that look sensible. There are certainly some other tries, but we are on unexplored territory here, so it's impossible to cover every imaginable idea. The first idea we will examine is the move  12.Nd2  intending to play b5-b6, the second one is  12.a5  going for Na4 and c4-c5. }
12. Nd2 Nh7 13. b5 Nc8
{ It is essential to avoid  13...a5?  as  14.b6!  would kill our Queenside.   The problem of  13...axb5?  14.axb5  is the strange position of the a7-Knight. It is under fire of the a1-Rook, but can't move. }
14. bxa6
{ Taking on a6 is logical anyway, as it creates a weakness on a6. We were also threatening ...a5 now, so White needed to change the structure.   Now, a6 is very weak and might even drop in the future, but we'll have counterplay on the other side of the board. }
