{ Kramnik reacted with  8...b5  . This move is fine, but we suggest playing  8...h6  first. If you don't play ...h6 soon, White might manage to play Qd2 and prevent ...h6. In this case, the Bishop stays on the h4-d8 diagonal, and we don't have the option to play ...g5 at a good moment.  In general, we advise playing ...h6 after Bg5 in the Classical. This applies to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  h6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  Nc6  8.Bg5  h6  and the line here. So just keep in mind to insert ...h6 after Bg5.  Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  Nc6  8.Bg5  h6  , White's usual choice is  9.Bh4  . Instead, after  9.Be3  e5  , we reach a position similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p1np1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N1P/PPP1BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3  e5  , but with the extra move ...h6 - clearly not a cause for concern.   Similarly, @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1ppb1/p1np1npp/6B1/3PP3/2N2N1P/PPP1BPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bf4  b5  is comparable to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bf4  Nc6  8.h3  b5  but with the extra tempo ...h6, which does not substantially differ. }
