ns of Be3/Bg5/Bc4 can be irritating at first. However, all the variations follow the same storyline: we try to achieve the target setup, while White tries to prevent it and gain control of d5.  Before we look at some moves, we'd like to mention that Black scores very well in the dxe5 positions, even though White should not be worse. One reason might be that White is often not prepared for the ...a6 & ...Nc6 lines and seeks a simple solution. If you have never studied it, closing the centre with d4-d5 is not an easy decision. It leads to positions that are much more in the spirit of the Classical King's Indian, quite a long way from what a 1.e4-player usually gets on the board.  We have seen that keeping the tension is unchallengeable, which leaves the dxe5 option. So frequently, White plays it as a 'cop out' with a somewhat weak mindset. We think this is the main reason for White's bad score, not the actual positions' quality.  There are players on the White side that play these positions to press small advantages and grind us down. But don't think that White is after simplifications and a draw after the exchange; looks can be deceiving. However, there will be players @@StartBracket@@see White's lousy score@@EndBracket@@ who view the trade on e5 as a way to avoid complications and simplify the game as much as possible. Against these players, it is crucial not to accept a draw readily but to continue playing and accumulating small advantages.  A good strategy can be to offer trades that are favourable for us. If White is too keen on exchanging all pieces, these offers can be tempting. Even sterile positions often can be won by pure persistence - play on until they break down. }
