ys @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.h3  O-O  6.Bf4  which we also answer with an ...a6-setup. The various versions can be treated in the same way, making it less confusing than it sounds first.   This general move order approach is identical to the one we use against the Be3 lines. We answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  with  4...a6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be3  with  5...a6  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.h3  O-O  6.Be3  with  6...a6  . We'll discuss the merits of the early ...a6! now. }
4... a6
{ Similar to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  a6!  line, we immediately start counterplay on the Queenside. We need to be aware of White's idea to play a quick Qd2 and Bh6, which is extremely dangerous.   The prime example is the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.Qd2  O-O  6.Bh6  , which is a recipe for disaster for Black. Our idea with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6!  is to speed up the Queenside play. If White plays Bh6, we can capture on h6 without having played ...Bg7 before, saving a tempo. The move Bh6 also wouldn't attack a Bishop on g7, which allows us to ignore Bh6 and let White take on f8.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  , we mostly need to consider  5.Qd2  and  5.Nf3  . The move  5.Nf3  we will answer with  5...Bg7  , which leads to a position that you will also get on the board via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Bf4  a6!   To sum things up: we handle the moves sequences @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  a6!  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be3  a6!  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bf4  a6!  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Bf4  a6!  in a very consistent fashion.  The Bishop moves to e3 and f4 signal White's possible plan to go Qd2 and Bh6, which means we should start our Queenside play immediately. }
