5... Bg7
{ After this natural move, White's main choice is between the aggressive  6.Qd2  , intending Bh6 and O-O-O, or a more restrained approach with moves like  6.h3  and  6.a4  . }
6. Qd2
{ White prepares to castle Queenside, the most ambitious and popular move. }
6... O-O
{ We think this is the most precise move. After  6...b5  7.Bd3!  White seems to better, based on a quick e4-e5. We advise castling instead. It is useful to look at a similar line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  a6  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Qd2  when we suggest  6...O-O  , too.   In both lines, the move  7.Bh6  is the most obvious and leads to the same position. We cover this critical line in the 4.Be3 move order, as it is the far more popular way to reach the same position. Instead of  7.Bh6  , White's main alternative is  7.O-O-O }
7. h4 { Very rare, we only found one game in our database with this move. }
7... h5
{ The simplest solution: we stop Harry in his tracks.  7...c5  also works quite well, but ...h5 is our usual way to treat h4 pushes.  Now we are ready to play in the centre with ...Nc6 and ...e5. having the g4-square is useful, too. }
