{ This is one of White's more aggressive setups. Similar to  4.Be3  White aims for rapid Queenside development.  Quite frequently, our opponent aims for Queenside castling and intends to launch a Kingside attack. But why does White play  4.Bg5  instead of  4.Be3?   After  4.Bg5  the Bishop is more active than on e3. It attacks our f6-Knight and we have to reckon with e4-e5 in many cases. Sounds great for White but there are drawbacks.  First of all, the Bishop might get kicked away with ...h6 and possibly ...g5. In some cases, White needs to give up the Bishop-pair, as we will see.  A second point, compared to Be3 setups, is the neglect of central control on d4 and c5. On e3 the Bishop helps to control those squares, while on g5, and often h4 later, this piece is not connected to the centre and Queenside action.   A crucial point to mention is that White's various continuations after  4...Bg7  -  5.Qd2  ,  5.f4  ,  5.Nf3  and  5.e5  - require different responses. There is no 'once size fits all' approach or a 'setup' to go for. Each line leads to different position types and needs a specific answer.   We will examine  4.Bg5  in two chapters. The present one covers all options for White after  4...Bg7  except the most popular move,  5.Qd2  , which is examined in a dedicated chapter. }
4... Bg7
{ A perfectly normal move, but we need to talk about it in more detail. On move four, White has three reasonable moves of the Queen's Bishop, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  ,  4.Bf4  , and  4.Bg5  . These moves share some common ideas, but also differ considerably in some ways.  In our repertoire, we handle the moves  4.Be3  and  4.Bf4  in the same way, by playing an immediate  4...a6!  to answer  5.Qd2  with  5...b5!  We keep the Bishop on f8 to take the sting out of White's Qd2 & Bh6 idea.  The line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  Bg7?!  5.Qd2  and next Bh6 scores particularly well for White and should be avoided. The same applies for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bf4  a6!  , as White's Bh6 idea works just as well with a Bishop on f4.  Now, let's look at @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  should we play  4...a6  here, too? No, this is a mistake due to  5.e5!  highlighting a critical difference between the Bishop placements.  Therefore we suggest playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bg7!  but what about  5.Qd2  then? Is this a problem due to Bh6 next, just like after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  Bg7?!  No, because this time we can benefit from the Bishop position on g5 by playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bg7  5.Qd2  h6!  which stops the exchange idea in its tracks. This line is coveredhere in the second chapter on  4.Bg5  , which focuses exclusively on  5.Qd2  , White's main move.  In the variations @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be3  and  4.Bf4  , we play  4