1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5
{ This is one of White's more aggressive setups. Similar to  4.Be3  White aims for rapid Queenside development.  Quite frequently, our opponent aims for Queenside castling and intends to launch a Kingside attack. But why does White play  4.Bg5  instead of  4.Be3?   After  4.Bg5  the Bishop is more active than on e3. It attacks our f6-Knight and we have to reckon with e4-e5 in many cases. Sounds great for White but there are drawbacks.  First of all, the Bishop might get kicked away with ...h6 and possibly ...g5. In some cases, White needs to give up the Bishop-pair, as we will see.  A second point, compared to Be3 setups, is the neglect of central control on d4 and c5. On e3 the Bishop helps to control those squares, while on g5, and often h4 later, this piece is not connected to the centre and Queenside action.   A crucial point to mention is that White's various continuations after  4...Bg7  -  5.Qd2  ,  5.f4  ,  5.Nf3  and  5.e5  - require different responses. There is no 'once size fits all' approach or a 'setup' to go for. Each line leads to different position types and needs a specific answer.   We will examine  4.Bg5  in two chapters. The present one covers all options for White after  4...Bg7  except the most popular move,  5.Qd2  , which is examined in a dedicated chapter. }
