...a6  , which defines our pawn structure on the Queenside early on. How do we handle our Queenside formation against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5?   This decision depends on White's fifth move and needs to be decided on a case-by-case basis. Some lines feature relatively uncommon ideas in the Pirc, involving the move ...d6-d5.   In the current chapter, we will focus on  5.f4  ,  5.e5  , and  5.Nf3  , while  5.Qd2  is coveredhere in a separate chapter. }
